netsquid.qubits.qstate

Definition of the QState base class. The assigned representation defines how the actual quantum state is represented.

class netsquid.qubits.qstate.QState(list qubits, QRepr representation=None)

Bases: object

A quantum state shared by qubits.

This class contains a set of qubits that consitute the shared quantum state. The quantum state is represented by its qrepr attribute, which is a subclass of QRepr.

Parameters:

  • qubits (list of Qubit) – Qubit objects that represent each qubit.

  • representation (QRepr or None, optional) – The representation of this quantum state. If None the state should be assigned manually via assign_qstate().

Raises:

  • ValueError – If qubits don’t have unique name attributes. If the number of qubits given doesn’t match the number of qubits the representation represents.

  • TypeError – If the given representation is not a QRepr subclass.

combine_qstate(self, QState other)

Combine this quantum state with another one.

Qubits of the other quantum state will adopt this one; the other quantum state can be discarded.

Parameters:

other (QState) – The other quantum state to combine with.

Raises:

  • QStateCombineError – If the quantum states are of an incompatible type.

  • RuntimeError – If not all Qubit names are unique.

Notes

For potential efficiency gains the order that the qubit’s states are combined is left unspecified i.e. the other_qstate is not necessarily appended, but may also be prepended.

compare(self, QState other_qstate)

Check if two quantum state representations are equal.

Parameters:

other_qstate (QState) – The other quantum state to combine with.

Returns:

True if the quantum state representations are equal.

Return type:

bool

Notes

The __eq__ operator is reserved for checking if the quantum states are the same instance.

drop_qubit(self, qubit, QRepr new_qrepr=None)

Drop a qubit from this quantum state.

The quantum state of the dropped qubit will become None.

Parameters:

  • qubit (Qubit) – Qubit to drop from the quantum state.

  • new_qrepr (QRepr, optional) – The new representation of this state after the qubit has been dropped. If not provided it is calculated via the QRepr.

Notes

If this is the only qubit in the quantum state, then the qubit is assigned None for its quantum state. For efficiency the quantum state object itself is not modified in this case but simply assumed to be lost i.e. it will continue to reference the dropped qubit (but not vice versa).
